# Strace-ing Node.js HTTP Handling

So why are we only able to handle 2-3 responses per millisecond? We straced
`engine_runner.js` and correlated the strace output with the standard responses.
The relevant outputs have been replicated below.

What we've observed:

  1. Node.js uses epoll_pwait on all the sockets to know when new data is available.
  2. It calls "read" on them soon after.
    a. The response times seem to be entirely based off of the "read" calls, not
       off of the epoll_pwait event (which retroactively should be recognized as
       the real HTTPS response time).
    b. It wouldn't be an issue if the time was based on the read calls if they
       all occured back to back, since they only take 0.05ms, however, node.js
       appears to be doing some form of processing in between the read calls
       and therefore they are spaced out by about ~1 ms.
    c. Since strace reports all the system calls in between read operations as taking
       effectively no time, the delay must be coming from processing in Node.js
       itself.

Some thoughts on next steps:

  1. See if simply setting response type to `buffer` instead of `text` in `got`
     removes the delay.
  2. Stop using `got` so that we have direct control over socket processing
  3. Don't do any processing w/ data from `request.on('data', data => ...)` until
     the next tick (using something like `setImmediate()`). Or just ignore the data
     entirely to see if an MVP can get Node.js to handle responses faster.
